column168: THE SHIPMENT INVOLVED WAS TENDERED TO THE CARGO FACILITY AT 1840/AUG10 AS MACHINE PARTS.  AIR WAYBILL 005 IAH 3712 2643 WAS COMPLETED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS TENDERED FOR FLIGHT 430/10AUG (AIRCRAFT 889), THE SHIPMENT DID NOT HAVE ANY ORIENTATION LABELS AFFIXED, NOR WAS IT DECLARED TO BE A "DANGEROUS GOODS".  IT APPEARS THE SHIPMENT WAS TURNED ON IT'S SIDE DURING THE LOADING PROCESS. AS A RESULT OF BEING ON IT'S SIDE THE GASOLINE (ESTIMATED TO BE FROM 1 TO 2 GALLONS) THAT REMAINED IN THE FUEL TANK, LEAKED OUT ON TO THE CARGO COMPARTMENT FLOOR. AFTER DEPARTURE THE FLIGHT ATTENDANTS REPORTED A STRONG ODOR OF GASOLINE TO THE COCKPIT CREW, AND IT WAS DETERMINED THE FLIGHT WOULD RETURN TO HOUSTON SO THE ODOR COULD BE INVESTIGATED. UPON THE AIRCRAFT'S RETURN TO THE GATE IN HOUSTON, THE SPILLAGE OF GASOLINE WAS DISCOVERED AND MAINTENANCE WAS ADVISED AND THE CARGO WAS REMOVED FROM THE AIRCRAFT. MAINTENANCE CLEANED UP THE SPILL, BUT TO EXPEDITE THE FLIGHT'S DEPARTURE THE AIRCRAFT WAS CHANGED TO A/C 880. THE CARGO WAS RETURNED TO THE CARGO FACILITY. EMERGENCY MEDICAL TECHNICIANS WERE AVAILABLE AT THE GATE, UPON THE RETURN OF THE FLIGHT AND THEY DETERMINED THAT FRESH AIR WAS ALL ANYONE NEEDED, OTHERWISE NO PASSENGER OR CREw MEMBER WAS TREATED OR HOSPITALIZED. IT WAS DETERMINED THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED A 'CAULKING MACHINE' THAT SHOULD HAVE BEEN TENDERED AS A DANGEROUS GOODS (ENGINES, INTERNAL COMBUSTION, UN3166) WITH THE FUEL TANK DRAINED.

THE N&M TRANSFER DRIVER LOADED THE FIRST OF TWO (55) GALLON OPEN HEAD DRUMS OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID WASTE ON THE LIFT GATE AND SLID IT FORWARD.  THE DRUM WAS PUSHED ALL THE WAY FORWARD.  WHEN THE LIFT GATE WAS ABOUT 8-12 INCHES OFF THE GROUND THE DRUM BEGAN TO SLIDE OFF.  THE DRUM HIT THE GROUND ON ITS SIDE AND AS A RESULT THE TOP OF THE DRUM BENT AND SOME LEAKAGE TOOK PLACE.  THE N&M TRANSFER DRIVER WAS NOT ABLE TO SECURE THE DRUM WHEN IT BEGAN TO MOVE BECAUSE HE WENT TO THE SIDE OF THE STRAIGHT TRUCK TO OPERATE THE LIFT GATE HANDLE.  THE SHOP FOREMAN AT THE SHIPPERS FACILITY WAS STANDING IN FRONT OF THE LIFT GATE AS IT BEGAN TO RISE.  WHEN ASKED WHY HE FAILED TO HOLD BACK THE DRUM FROM SLIDING, HE REPLIED THAT HE THOUGHT IT WOULD BE TOO HEAVY.  THIS N&M TRANSFER DRIVER HAS NOW BEEN INSTRUCTED TO HAVE OTHER SHIPPING PERSONNEL OPERATE THE LIFT GATE HANDLE. HE IS NOW AWARE THAT HIS DUTY WHILE LOADING WILL BE TO SECURE ALL CONTAINERS FROM SLIDING OFF THE LIFT GATE.  THIS SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY SUPERIOR ENVIRONMENTAL, SHEBOYGAN, WISCONSIN.  THE WISCONSIN DNR AND THE NATIONAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER WERE NOTIFIED BY TELEPHONE.

CSXT CALLED FERGUSON HARBOUR AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, TO RESPOND.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT OPENED THE VALVE UP STREAM OF THE PRESSURE GAUGE, WHICH NORMALLY IS CLOSED BUT WAS OPENED. THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE LEAK AT THE GAUGE STOPPED.  FERGUSON HARBOUR CHECKED ALL VALVES IN THE VALVE BOX TO MAKE SURE THEY WERE TIGHTLY CLOSED. THE CONTAINER WAS SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER FOR COMPLETE INSPECTION OF ALL VALVES.

HYDROGEN TRAILER (SN 613052) WAS LOADED AT SARNIA, ONTARIO, AND DISPATCHED TO GLENMONT, NEW YORK, ON AUGUST 17TH, 2100 HOURS.  THE INTERNAL VESSEL PRESSURE WAS 8 PSIG.  DURING TRANSIT, THE PRESSURE REMAINED STABLE AT 8 PSIG UNTIL A SAFETY CHECK AT 0445 ON AUGUST 18 INDICATED A PRESSURE OF 17 PSIG.  AT THIS TIME, THE DRIVERS RECEIVED INSTRUCTIONS FROM THEIR HOME TERMINAL TO SWITCH TO THE 50 PSI SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  THE NEXT SAFETY CHECK AT 0715 REVEALED A PRESSURE RISE TO 30 PSIG.  THE DRIVERS WERE INSTRUCTED TO MOVE TO A SAFE, ISOLATED AREA TO CONDUCT A CONTROLLED VENTING. AFTER VENTING DOWN TO 18 PSIG, THE DRIVERS CONTINUED TRANSIT TO GLENMONT WITHOUT FURTHER BLOW DOWN AND STABILIZE THE TRAILER BEFORE IT DEPARTED SARNIA.  THIS PROCEDURE HAS BEEN RECLARIFIED WITH THOSE INVOLVED.

WHILE REMOVING FREIGHT FROM PALLET PMC6175LH, BOXES FELL OFF OF PALLET CONTAINING THE ABOVE SUBSTANCE AND STARTED TO LEAK. THEY MOISTENED OTHER PACKAGES CONTAINING THE SAME SUBSTANCE. A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM ACE HARDWARE PAINT DIVISION LOCATED AT 21901 S CENTRAL AVENUE  IN MATTESON IL TO SYSTECH ENVIRONMENTAL LOCATED AT MILE MARKER 235 ON I-44 WEST OF ST.CLAIRE, MO. PRIOR TO DEPARTING THE REST AREA, THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT MATERIAL WAS LEAKING FROM THE REAR DOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS OF MATERIAL ONTO THE ASPHALT PAVEMENT OF THE REST AREA.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED THE RELEASED MATERIAL WITH A SUITABLE ABSORBENT AND PLACED A 5 GALLON PAIL UNDER THE LEAK. HE THEN NOTIFIED HIS DISPATCHER WHO DISPATCHED A CLEAN-UP CREW TO THE SCENE TO IDENTIFY THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK AND INITIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.  IN ADDITION, BOTH THE MISSOURI STATE POLICE & THE MISSOURI DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES WERE INFORMED OF THE INCIDENT.  UPON EXAMINATION OF THE CARGO, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT MATERIAL HAD LEAKED FROM THE TOP LIDS OF THREE DRUMS AND THE BOTTOM CHIME OF THE FOURTH. ALL DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED INTO SALVAGE DRUMS ALONG WITH THE CLEAN-UP DEBRIS AND WERE SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS SISTUATION, ALL PERSONNEL INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO CHECK NOT ONLY THE STRUCTURAL INTEGRITY OF EACH CONTAINER BUT ALSO TO INSURE THAT THE LIDS, RINGS AND GASKETS ARE PRESENT, FREE OF ANY DEFECTS AND PROPERLY SECURED.

IN ADDITION, THE MASSACHUSETTS STATE POLICE, WESTBORO FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE MASSACHUSETTS DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT. UPON EXAMINATION OF THE CARGO, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE BOTTOM SEAM OF THE DRUM FAILED RESULTING IN THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 35 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR DRIVER WAS TRAVELING SOUTH BOUND ON COLORADO 285 APPROXIMATELY 5 MILES NORTH OF BAILEY COLO AS OUR UNIT STARTED DOWN A SHORT DOWNGRADE THE DRIVER NOTICED THE VEHICLE AHEAD OF HIM BEGIN TO SWERVE AND FISHTAIL ALL OVER THE ROAD.  OUR DRIVER FEARED THE CAMPER TRAILER WOULD OVERTURN RIGHT IN FRONT OF HIM AND HE MOVED TO THE RIGHT HAND SIDE OF THE LANE TO ALLOW AS MUCH ROOM AS POSSIBLE TO TRY TO AVOID THE CAMP TRAILER IF IT WOULD FLIP. CONSEQUENTLY HE GOT TO CLOSE TO THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE ROAD AND DROPPED THE RIGHT FRONT TIRE OFF INTO A SOFT SANDY SHOULDER.  THE SOFT SHOULDER MATERIAL PULLED THE TRUCK FARTHER ONTO THE SHOULDER AND AS THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO GET THE VEHICLE ONTO THE ROAD, THE HIGHWAY MADE A LEFT HAND CURVE.  THE SOFT MATERIAL, THE CURVE AND SPEED OF THE VEHICLE ALL TOGETHER CAUSED THE TRUCK AND TRAILER TO ROLL OVER ONTO THE RIGHT SIDE AND COME TO A REST ON THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE ROAD.  AS SOON AS WE WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT WE CALLED RIEDEL ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICE INC. TO RESPOND TO THE LEAKING DOME LID, CALLED MERRIT WRECKER SERVICE TO HELP RIGHT THE VEHICLE AND GROENDYKE  TRANSPORT TO SEND AN EMPTY TANK TRAILER TO THE SCENE SO WE COULD TRANSFER THE LOAD FROM THE LEAKING TANK.  THE COLORADO STATE PATROL, PARK COUNTY SHERRIFF DEPUTY'S AND LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE ALREADY ON THE SCENE AT THE TIME WE WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

AS THE DRUM WAS BEING RAISED TO THE BACK OF THE VEHICLE THE DRUM LID SEPARATED FROM DRUM CAUSING IT TO DROP TO THE GROUND SPILLING SOME OF ITS CONTENTS. IT HAS BEEN DETERMINED THAT THE LID WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED BEFORE LIFTING THE DRUM AND WAS THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT, AS OPPOSED TO EQUIPMENT FAILURE. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED AND RECOVERED BY THE SAFETY KLEEN REPRESENTATIVE ON SCENE, IT WAS DRUMMED, LABELED AND MANIFESTED FOR SHIPMENT TO OUR W.BROOKFIELD FACILITY, IT WILL IN TURN BE SENT TO A SAFETY KLEEN CORP. RECYCLE CENTER FOR ULTIMATE DISPOSAL AND OR TREATMENT. THE LEOMINSTER FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THIS INCIDENT AT THE REQUEST OF SAFETY KLEEN CORP. DEPUTY CHIEF HALLORAN IS ON SCENE AND IS SATISFIED WITH OUR CLEAN UP EFFORTS. THERE WAS NO THREAT TO GROUND WATER, SEWERS OR SOIL AND THERE WHERE NO INJURIES AS A RESULT OF THIS RELEASE.  TO PREVENT THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT AGAIN MORE CARE WILL BE TAKEN TO SECURE DRUM LIDS BEFORE MOVING OR HOISTING DRUMS.

IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS SITUATION, DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSPECT THE STRUCTURAL INTEGRITY OF EACH CONTAINER ACCEPTED FOR TRANSPORTATION PRIOR TO PLACING ON THE VEHICLE. WHILE PROCEEDING EAST ON ROUTE 6 IN BOLTON CT, DRIVER NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM REAR OF TRAILER.  HE PULLED OVEN ON SHOULDER MAKING SURE IT WAS SAFE, NO STORM DRAINS, ETC.  HE TOOK A SHOVEL AND BUILT A LITTLE DIRT DAM TO CONTAIN THE LIQUID.  HE RADIOED ON CHANNEL 9 AND ASKED A TRUCKER TO CALL 911.  HE ALSO FLAGGED DOWN A HIGHWAY TRUCK AND ASKED THEM TO GIVE THEM MANIFEST ADVISE.  MANIFEST ADVISED THEM OF SITUATION AND WENT TO SAFE AREA AS HE WAS INSTRUCTED. CARGO TANK DRIVER UNLOADING DIESEL FUEL FROM CARGO TANK INTO ABOVE GROUND FUEL STORAGE TANK.  AT COMPLETION OF UNLOADING PROCESS DRIVER FAILED TO CLOSE LINE VALVE PRIOR TO SHUTTING OFF PUMP.  CHECK VALVE IN PUMP FAILED CAUSING ININTENTIONAL RELEASE OF 15 TO 25 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL INTO THE RETAINER AREA AROUND THE STORAGE TANK.  SOIL REMOVED FROM THE SPILL AREA WAS PLACED ON BLACK PLASTIC FOR AIRING.  SOIL SAMPLES HAVE BEEN SENT TO A TESTING LAB TO DETERMINE EXTENT OF CONTAMINATION.  RESULTS OF SOIL TEST WILL DETERMINE DISPOSAL OF THE SOIL ACCORDING TO ALL LOCAL AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.  NEW FUEL LINE CHECK VALVES HAVE BEEN INSTALLED TO PREVENT RE-OCCURANCE AND DRIVER TRAINING HAS BEEN REQUIRED OF DRIVER INVOLVED.
NO REMARKS

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM ACCO USA, INC. LOCATED AT 770 S.  ACCO PLAZA IN WHEELING, IL TO PETROCHEM PROCESSING, INC. LOCATED AT 420 LYCASTE IN DETROIT, MI.  DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO, INC. LOCATED IN CHICAGO, IL, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A 55 GALLON CONTAINER HAD DEVELOPED A PINHOLE LEAK ON THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF MATERIAL ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRANSPORT VEHICLE WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIROMENT. PERSONNEL FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF CHICAGO, INC. IMMEDIATELY OVERPACKED THE CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM AND ABSORBED THE RELEASED MATERIAL WITH SPEEDI DRY. ALL CLEAN-UP MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN THE SALVAGE DRUM AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY  INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  PRIOR TO LOADING AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED. ALLL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS (I.E. OVERPACKING A LEAKING CONTAINER) IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE LEAKING ENROUTE.

AFTER LOADING MEA AT UNION CARHIDE N. SEADRIFT, TX DRIVER PROCEED TO TERMINAL IN ANGLETON, TX TO DROP TRAILER PRIOR TO PROCEEDING FOR DELIVERY. TRAILER WAS TRANS LOADED TO ANOTHER DSI TRAILER AFTER APPROVAL BY UNION CARHIDE PERSONNEL.

column168: THIS WAS A COFC SHIPMENT THAT WAS BEING PREPARED FOR LOADING FROM THE FIRST TRANSPORTER (KS & D) TO THE SECOND TRANSPORTER (UNION PACIFIC RAIL) THE KS & D DRIVER UNHOOKED THE CABLE SECURING THE LOAD TO THE TRAILER TO ALLOW THE PACKER TO LIFT THE CONTAINER.  THE PACKER OPERATOR REQUESTED THE TRUCK TO BE MOVED UNDER THE PACKER.  THE KS & D DRIVER DID NOT RE-SECURE THE CONTAINER AND IT ROLLED OFF THE BACK OF THE TRAILER TO THE GROUND. THE IMPACT OF THE DROP BROKE THE REAR CHAINS OF THE CONTAINER ALLOWING THE UNLOADING DOOR TO OPEN. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. HAZMAT TEAM WAS CALLED AND RESPONDED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A FRONT END LOADER AND CLEANUP TEAM WOULD BE NEEDED BUT THERE WAS NO IMMEDIATE DANGER TO HUMAN HEALTH OR ENVIRONMENT. CLEANUP WAS PERFORMED BY HERITAGE ENVIRONMENTAL. ALL KS &D DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO NEVER RELEASE THE SECURING CABLE UNTIL THE PACKER IS HOOKED TO THE CONTAINER TO PREVENT THIS TYPE OF INCIDENT FROM RE-OCCURRING.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: INCIDENT:  DURING TRANSPORT, A TRANSFORMER CONTAING POLYCHLORINATED BIPHENY (PCB) OIL (550 PARTS PER MILLION), BECAME UNSECURED DUE TO ABRUPT STOP OF TRANSPORT VEHICLE IN EFFORT TO AVOID COLLISION WITH ANOTHER VEHICLE.  TRANSFORMER TIPPED OVER IN BED OF TRUCK, SPILLING OIL UNTO TRUCK BED, ENTRACE RAMP AND HIGHWAY 169.  REPORTING:  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CITY OF MAPLE GROVE, MNDOT, MN POLLUTION CONTROL AGNECY, NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER/US DOT.  RESPONSE:  MNDOT AND NSP CREWS ARRIVED IMMEDIATELY TO CONTAIN SPILL AND SECURE SITE.  THE ENTRANCE RAMP UNTO HWY 169 AND ONE LANE ON HWY 169 NEAR THE ENTRANCE RAMP WAS CLOSED.  BAY WEST INC. (EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR) ARRIVED AT 1600 TO ASSIST NSP CREWS IN THE CLEAN-UP THROUGH THE NIGHT.  UPON APPROVAL FROM STATE AGENCY OFFICIALS, ONE LANE ON HWY 169 THAT WAS PARTIALLY BARRICADED WAS REOPENED AT 1500 ON 8/18/93. FURTHER CLEAN-UP AND SAMPLING WAS CONDUCTED ON THE ENTRACE RAMP AND SHOULDER OF HWY 169.  AFTER TEST RESULTS SHOWED ADEQUATE CLEAN-UP FOR PCBS, STATE AGENCY OFFICIALS OPENED THE ENTRANCE RAMP ON 8/24/93 AT APPROXIMATELY 1500.  PREVENTION:  MANAGEMENT WITHIN SEVERAL AFFECTED DEPARTMENTS AT NSP HAS MET TO DETERMINE FURTHER PREVENTATIVE ACTIONS FOR IMPLEMENTATION THROUGHOUT NSP.

PRODUCT IN THE PROCESS OF BEING UNLOADED, AIR PRESSURE WAS APPLIED TO TANK- TANK STARTED TO LEAK UNDER THE SKIN - NEAR OUTLET VALVE, LOAD WAS DELIVERED VIA PUMP WITHOUT INCIDENT. EMPLOYEE WAS LOADING DRUM USING A BARREL TRUCK.  THE DRUM SLIPPED OFF THE BARREL TRUCK AND STRUCK THE METAL FOOT ON THE BARREL TRUCK PUNCTURING THE DRUM. THE BARREL TRUCK WAS TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE FOR REPAIR AND THE EMPLOYEE CONSELLED ON PROPER HANDLING OF DRUMS.

column168: DRIVER WAS ADVISED THAT PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM REAR OF TRAILER AND A WHITE CLOUD WAS COMING OUT FROM THE REAR. THE STATE POLICE, BEING UNSURE OF COMMDITY ON TRAILER EVACUATED THE TRUCKSTOP.  THE COMPANY IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WHO DETERMINED THAT A PALLET OF BOXES SHIFTED AND HIT THE STACKED PAILS, CAUSING THE BANDS AROUND THE PAILS TO BECOME DISLODGED AND LOOSENED FALLING OFF THE PAILS.  THE RESULT WAS THE PAILS BECAME LOOSE IN THE TRAILER, ONE PAIL BEING PUNCTURED AND CONTENTS LEAKD OUT.  THE CONTENTS RAN OUT THE BACK OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE HOT TIRES OF TRAILER AND VAPORIZED. column168: THE TRUCK DRIVER PULLED INTO THE UNLOADING AREA, ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE BULK PLANT, HOOKED UP AND STARTED PUMPING DIESEL FUEL INTO TANK #1. HE DID NOT "WALK THE LINE", TO CHECK ALL THE VALVES TO INSURE FUEL COULD ONLY GO INTO TANK #1. ALL THE VALVES (C,D, & E, SEE MAP) HAD BEEN OPENED OR LEFT OPEN, ALLOWING FUEL TO GO THROUGH THE PUMP HOUSE OUT THROUGH THE LOADOUT NOZZLES. WHEN THE DRIVER DID SEE THE FUEL RUNNING OUT, HE STOPPED PUMPING-SHUT DOWN VALVES D &E AND FINISHED UNLOADING. AT 7:30 AM, HE CALLED THE MAIN OFFICE AND REPORTED THE SPILL TO ME. THE TANK HAD 11" OF FUEL WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED, AND 62 1/4" WHEN HE FINISHED, EQUALING 3034 GAL. THE TDR WAS THE TANK READING, FOUND A PUDDLE OF FUEL WHICH WE PUMPED INTO BARRELS, APPROXIMATELY 70 GALLONS. WE THEN DUG UP THE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND PLACED IT ON SHEETS OF PLASTIC, AWAITING FINAL DISPOSAL AND INSTRUCTIONS FROM CDH.

CUSTOMER UNLOADING LINE BROKE DURING UNLOADING.

JOHN NADUAD (DOCKWORKER) WAS UNLOADING A TRAILER WHEN A CARTON CONTAINING PYRIDINE FELL OFF A SKID AND BROKE OPEN.  THE DOCKWORKER TRIED TO PICK UP CASE AND GET IT OFF THE TRAILER WITHOUT PROPER CLOTHING AND WAS OVERCOME BY THE FUMES.  A HAZ MAT TEAM WAS CALLED IN TO CLEAN UP.

ON THE AFTERNOON OF AUGUST 4, 1993, PVS-NOLWOOD TRAILER #50A WAS LOADED WITH 3000 GALLONS OF 2 BAUME' (31%) HYDROCHLORIC ACID FOR DELIVERY TO AJAX METAL PROCESSING, INC.  4651 BELLVUE, DETROIT, MICHIGAN.  THE RUBBER-LINED TRAILER HAS A CAPACITY OF 6000 GALLONS WHEN FULL.  THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE AJAX FACILITY AT APPROXIMATELY 5:20PM.  ACCORDING TO THE DRIVER, AFTER HE HAD OBTAINED PERMISSION FROM AJAX PERSONNEL TO HOOK UP THE TRAILER AND UNLOAD, HE WENT BACK TO THE TRUCK, DONNED HIS PERSONAL PROTECTION GEAR, AND HOOKED UP THE TRAILER FOR UNLOADING.  HE RETURNED TO THE TRUCK CAB AND STARTED THE AIR COMPRESSOR TO PRESSURIZE.  WHILE WAITING THE USUAL 10 MINUTES FOR THE AIR PRESSURE TO BUILD SUFFICIENTLY, HE NOTICED IN HIS SIDE VIEW MIRROR THAT PRODUCT WAS SPILLING OVER THE TOP OF THE TRUCK.  HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE COMPRESSOR AND THE TRUCK AND CLIMBED TO THE TRAILER TOP AND CLOSED THE MANUEL PRODUCT VALVE, BUT THE LEAK DID NOT STOP.  HE TRIED TO RELEIVE THE AIR PRESSURE ON THE TRAILER CONTENES BY OPENING THE "DUMP" VALVE, BUT WHEN LIQUID STARTED TO COME OUT OF THE VALVE HE CLOSED IT AGAIN.  (HE ASSUMED IT WAS HYDROCHLORIC ACID).  HE COULDN'T GET TO THE AIR PRESSURE VALVE BECAUSE OF ACID.  AT THIS POINT, THE DRIVER CALLED HIS SUPERVISOR FOR HELP.  AJAX PERSONNEL CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT, THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER, AND THE DETROIT WATER AND SEWAGE DEPARTMENT.  FIRE DEPARTMENT AND POLICE DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL CORDONED OFF BELVUE TO RESTRICT PUBLIC ACCESS.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: STATED TRUCK WAS ENROUTE FROM TULSA, OK., TO DE SOTO, KS, LOADED WITH MOLTEN SULPHUR.  THE TRUCK WAS NORHBOUND ON DOUGLAS COUNTY HIGHWAY 1061 APPROACHING THE INTERSECTION OF ROADWAY 600 N.  ON AUGUST 17,1993 AT APPROXIMATELY 2:45 P.M., THE TRUCK LEFT THE ROADWAY AND ENTERED THE EAST DITCH APPROXIMATELY 328 FEET SOUTH OF ROADWAY CROSSING 600 N *SEE ATACED REPORT*.  THE TRUCK THEN TRAVELED APPROXIMATELY 215 FEET STRIKING A PRIVAE DRIVEWAY CAUSING TEH VEHICLE TO BECOME AIRBORNE FOR APPROXIMATELY 13 FEET. THE TRUCK CONTINUED NORTHBOUND IN THE EAST DITCH WHERE IT TURNED ON ITS SIDE APPROXIMATELY 43 FEET SOUTH OF ROADWAY 600 N.  THE TRUCK THEN TRAVELED APPROXIMATLEY 70 ADDITIONAL FEET ON ITS SIDE BEFORE COMING TO REST ON ITS RIGHT TOP SIDE.  IT APPEARS THE RIGHT, REAR PORTION OF THE TRAILER STRUCK A UTILITY POLE CAUSING AN APPROXIMATE 8 INCH SPILT OR RUPTURE. THE CONTENTS SPILLED INTO THE DITCH, TRAVELED APPROXIMATELY 40 FEET, WHERE IT WAS CONTAINED WITH AN EARTHEN DIKE.  DUE TO PENDING AUTOPSY, DRIVER CAUSATION IS UNKNOW; THEREFORE, NO RECOMMENDATIONS ARE BEING SUBMITTED AT THIS TIME.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS ENROUTE TO HI DESTINATION.  HE STOPED TO EAT AND WHEN HE RETURNED TO HIS VEHICLE TO CONTINUE HE NOTED A DRIP OF LIUQID FROM THE BELLY OF HIS TRAILER.  AN INSPECTION OF HIS UNIT WHEN HE ARRIVED AT THE STOP DID NOT REVEAL ANY LEAK.  HE SECURED HIS UNIT AND PLACED A CONTAINER UNDER THE DRIP  HE CALLED HIS TERMINAL AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO DISPATCH ANOTHER TRAILER TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL.  THE TRANSFER WAS ACCOMPLISHED AND AND OUR DRIVER CONTINUED TO HIS DESTINATION.  THE LEAKING TANK WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE FOR REPAIR.

WHLE THE TANKER WAS BEING SAMPLED THE DRIVER CHECKED THE SRUBBER FOR LIQUIDS.  AS THE DRIVER MOVED THE TANKER TO THE STAGING AREA TO WAIT FOR UNLOADING APPROVAL, SOME MATERIAL CAME OUT OF THE SCRUBBER DRAIN LINE. THE TANKER WAS TAKEN TO A CONTAINMENT AREA, AND A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE DRAIN LINE.  APPROXIMATELY 1 OUNNCE OF MATERIAL HAD RELEASED AT THAT POINT.  THE TANKER WAS LATER GIVEN APPROVAL TO BE UNLOADED AND APPROXIMATELY 1 OUNCE OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED AGAIN FROM THE DRAIN LINE. THE TANK WAS UNLOADED AND REPAIRS WERE MADE TO THE DRAIM LINE TO PREVENT THIS IN THE FUTURE.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND AREA WERE SPILL OCCURRED WERE CLEANED IMMEDIATLEY FOLLOWING THE RELEASES.

BOX WAS FOUND CRUSHED. APPARENTLY RUN OVER BY A CONTAINER TRANSPORT VEHICLE.  INSPECTION OF INNER CONTAINERS SHOWED SOME DAMAGE BUT I WAS ASSUMED THAT THE VAIL WAS INTACT.  ANDRE RICHARDSON THEN OPEN THE LEAD PIG AND FOUND THE VAIL BROKE.  AT THAT TIME I CONTACTED DR ROY PARKER, OUR HEALTH PHYSICIST CONSULTANT, WHO REQUESTED THAT I RRESPOND TO THE SITE FOR CONTAMINATION SURVEYS.  I THEN RESPONDED AND FOUND SLIGHT CONTAMINATION ON PACKAGE, HUB'S SURVEY METER, AND ANDRE'S AND MY HANDS.  I THEN CLEANED AFFECTED AREAS AND CAPTURED THE CLEAN UP EQUIPMENT FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. THE STATE RADIOLOGICAL HEALTH PERSONNEL WERE ALSO CONTACTED WHO CAME OUT MADE ALL SURVEYS AND FOUND SMALL AMOUNTS OF CONTAMINATION THAT WERE ALSO CLEANED UP.  THE HUB EMPLOYEES WERE REMINDED NEVER TO OPEN UP A SUSPECTED DAMAGED RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL PACKAGE WITHOUT BEING INSTRUCTED BY OUR RADIATION HEALTH PHYSICIST.

ABOUT 35-40 MINUTES LATER PIEDMONT AVATION RE-TENDERED THE PACKAGE.  THEY SAID THAT THEY HAD PURGED AND CLEANED THE CONTENTS.  AGAIN THE BOX BEGAN EMITTING STRONG FUMES.  AT THAT POINT LORI AVERA CALLED ME AND I TOLD HER TO SECURE THE BOX BUT TO KEEP IT IN AN OPEN-AIR AREA.  I NOTIFIED THE FAA AND THEY ASKED THAT WE HOLD THE FREIGHT FOR THEM.  I ALSO NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER THAT THE BOX WOULD NOT BE FORWARDED.  THE FAA INVESTIGATED, RELEASED THE PACKAGE AND THE SHIPPER HAS PICKED IT UP.

INCIDENT OCCURED DURING OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT.  THE PACKAGE WAS GOING THROUGH THE PRIMARY SORT MATRIX WHEN THE PACKAGE WAS STRUCK BY A PACKAGE DIVERTER.  THE SMALL WHITE FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINING TWO 50ML GLASS BOTTLES WAS DAMAGED AND TAKEN OFF THE BELT.  UPON FURTHER EXAMIMNATION OF THE DAMAGED PACKAGE IT WAS FOUND THAT ONE OF THE INNER GLASS CONTAINERS HAD BEEN BROKEN AND LEAKED.  IT WAS ALSO DISCOVERED THAT THE TWO FIFTY MILLILITER GLASS BOTTLES BORE FLAMMABLE WARNING STICKERS.  THERE WERE NO OTHER MARKINGS, LABELS, NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S CERTIFICATION ATTACHED TO THE PACKAGE.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND WAS ASKED TO SEND AN SMDS TO HELP CLARIFY THE IDENTIFICATION OF THE MATERIAL WHICH WAS PRIMARILLY A DIAGNOSTIC REAGENT.  IT WAS FOUND THAT THE MATERIAL HAD A FLASHPOINT OF 50 DEGREES WHICH CAUSED US TO HOLD THE PACKAGE IN THE HUB SORT PENDING INVESTIGATION BY F.A.A.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET IN BALTIMORE, MD TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CONNECTICUT, INC. LOCATED AT 51 BRODERICK ROAD IN BRISTOL, CT. DURING A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBOR'S ALBANY SERVICE CENTER LOCATED IN GLENMONT, NY, THE DRIVER NOTICED A SMALL DRIP COMING FROM THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT OF THE SEREVICE CENTER.  A CONTAINMENT PAIL WAS IMMEDIATELY PLACED UNDER THE DRIP AND ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS SPREAD OVER THE RELEASED MATERIAL.  PERSONNEL FROM CLEAN HARBOR'S ALBANY SERVICE CENTER IMMEDIATELY IDENTIFIED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK AND OVERPACKED THE CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM AND DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY INDICATED ON THE ORIGINAL SHIPPING DOCUMENT.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED PRIOR TO LOADING AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING OR DAMAGE WAS OBSERVED.  IT IS SUSPECTED THAT THE DRUM CONTAINED DEFECTIVE LINER THAT ALLOWED THE LADING TO COME IN CONTACT WITH THE STEEL DRUM CAUSING A DEGRADATION OF THE BASIC PACKAGING MATERIAL OF THE CONTAINER.  ALL DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTIONS (I.E. OVERPACKING A LEAKING CONTAINER) IN THE EVENT A CONTAINER IS FOUND TO BE LEAKING ENROUTE.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1120 WEDNESDAY, AUGUST 25, 1993 AT CONRAIL'S LINDEN YARD IN LINDEN, NJ, THE ABOVE TANK CAR (TILX 260096) WAS DISCOVERED DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR.  AN INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR REVEALED THAT THE TOP GAUGING VALVE WAS PARTIALLY OPEN ALLOWING PRODUCT TO LEAK DOWN THE TANK BETWEEN THE SHELL AND OUTER JACKET.  AFTER CLOSING THE VALVE, PRODUCT CONTINUE TO DROP FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR.  UNABLE TO INSPECT THE INNER TANK SHELL, A PRECAUTIONARY DECISION WAS MADE TO TRANSFER THE COMMODITY INTO TANK TRUCKS.  DANA CORP. COMPLETED THE TRANSFER INTO TRUCKS AT 1920 HOURS.  OH MATERIALS WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE FOR ANY NECESSARY ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN-UP.  AN EXEMPTION WILL BE REQUESTED AND THE TANK CAR FORWARDED TO RESCAR, DUBOIS, PA.

WHEN OUR DRIVER STOPPED AT THE SCALE AND HIS UNIT WAS INSPECTED IT WAS NOTED THAT THERE WAS MOISTURE AROUND THE VALVE AT THE LAST COMPARTMENT. IT WAS NOT DROPPING ONT THE GROUND.  OUR DRIVER WAS ABLE TO CORRECT THE SITUATION AND CONTINUE ON TO HIS DESTINATION.  WE APOLOGIZE FOR THE LATE REPORT.  OUR DRIVER DID NOT REPORT THE INCIDENT SINCE THER WAS NO ACTUAL LOSS OF PRODUCT.

I HAVE ENCLOSED STATEMENTS FROM OUR DRIVER AND CORPORATE AIR, WHICH EXPLAIN CIRCUMSTANCES.  WHERE THE EXTRA FUEL CAME FROM IS UNKNOWN.  WE CHECKED THE 4 PREVIOUS LOADS HAULED BY THIS SET OF TRAILERS AND FOUND NO SHORTAGES.  THE ONLY OTHER POSSIBILITIES ARE THAT THE METERS AT THE PIPELINE WERE OFF OR THE STICK READING CORPORATE AIR TOOK WERE OFF. BECAUSE OF WHERE THE OVERFILL ALARM IS SET, EVERYONE HAS GOT INTO A HABIT OF SHUTTING IT OFF AND CONTINUING TO UNLOAD.  DIXON BROS., INC. AND CORPORATE AIR HAVE DECIDED IN THE FUTURE WHEN THE ALARM GOES OFF EVERYTHING IS SHUT DOWN LIKE IT IS SUPPOSE TO BE DONE THEN A CHECK THE TANK TO FIND HOW MUCH PRODUCT IT WILL HOLD AND THEN CHECK CARGO TANK TO FIND OUT HOW MUCH PRODUCT IS REMAINING.

ONE WHEEL ON THE PORTABLE TANK BROKE THROUGH THE DECK OF THE TRAILER, THEN A SECOND WHEEL, ON THE SAME SIDE OF THE TANK, BROKE THROUGH THE TRAILER ALLOWING THE TANK TO TIP OVER STRIKING ANOTHER PARKED VEHICLE, BREAKING A VALVE, CAUSING THE SPILL.  THE OPINION OF THE CARRIER IS THAT THE PROCEDURES FOR UNLOADING USED BY THE CONSIGNEE ARE UNSAFE AND DIRECTLY CONTRIBUTED TO THE INCIDENT.

CSXT'S TRAIN R534-26 DERAILED 18 CARS AT TUNNEL HILL, KY. (MP=36.4).  3 TANKS OF VINYLIDENE CHLORIDE AND 1 TANK CAR OF HYDROGEN FLUORIDE WERE DERAILED ON THEIR SIDES.  ON 8/27, WHILE RERAILING THE 3RD TANK CAR, IT WAS FOUND THAT GATX 24741, VINYLIDENE CHLORIDE HAD A PUNCTURE IN  THE A END JUST ABOVE THE COUPLER AND HAD RELEASED ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS.  VISUAL INSPECTIONS AND AIR MONITORING EQUIPMENT DID NOT DETECT THE RELEASE. CSXT'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, OHM CORP, SURVEYED THE AREA AND FOUND THE SPILLED PRODUCTS HAD FLOWED 150 FT DOWN THE MOUNTAINSIDE AND ALONG A STORM WATER RUN OFF CREEK BED.  RECOVERY AND CLEAN UP EFFORTS WERE HAMPERED BY THE INACCESSIBLE TERRAIN.  THE HYDROGEN FLUORIDE CAR WAS MOVED TO THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY FOR UNLOADING AND THE REMAINING 2 VENYLIDENE CHLORIDE CARS WERE TRANSLOADED AT LOUISVILLE, KY ON 9/9/93.

column168: DRIVER ARRIVED AT CHEMTECH WITH A LOADED TRAILER.  HE WAS ASKED TO BACK HI S TRAILER ON TO THE PAD TO BE UNLOADED.  HE UNHOOKED TRAILER #101 AND THEN HOOKED TO TRAILER #116.  DRIVER BEGAN PULLING AWAY AND IMMEDIATELY NOTICED MATERIAL SLOSHING OUT OF THE DOME.  HE STOPPED HIS TRUCK AT ONCE.  THE DRIVER, ALONG WITH PERSONNEL FROM CHEMTECH, IMMEDIATELY CLEANED THE MATERIAL OFF THE CEMENT WITH OIL DRY.  THEY ALSO CLEANED THE TRAILER WITH ABSORBENT PADS.  CHEMTECH THEN DISPOSED OF THE OIL DRY AND PADS.  THERE WAS NO COST ASSOCIATED WITH THIS INCIDENT.  ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS: WE ISSUED A LETTER TO ALL DRIVERS STATING THE IMPORTANCE OF THE PRE-TRIP INSPECTIONS AND AGAIN WENT OVER THE PROCEDURE IN OUR SAFETY MEETINGS.

column168: WILLIAM CUNNINGHAM WAS EMPLOYED AT MYERS CHEMICAL TRANSPORT, LTD AS A TRUCK WASHER.  WHILE REMOVING THE HOSES FROM THE TROUGH OF A TANKER, HE HAD TO FIRST REMOVE THE END CAP ON THE HOSE.  WHEN HE TRIED TO REMOVE THE CAP, MATERIAL THAT WAS LEFT IN THE HOSE SPLASHED ON HIS FACE.  HIS FACE WAS IMMEDIATELY FLUSHED WITH WATER AND HE WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL EMERGENCY ROOM.  HE WAS LATER RELEASED AND TOLD TO APPLY COLD COMPRESSES TO HIS FACE. HE FULLY RECOVERED AND RETURNED TO WORK ON 8-17-93.  THE ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS TYPE WERE TO CAUTION DRIVERS ABOUT MAKING SURE ALL HOSES ARE FULLY EMPTIED BEFORE REPLACING IN TROUGH.  ALSO, ALL PERSONNEL ARE REQUIRED TO WEAR SAFETY GOGGLES WHILE WORKING.

LOUIS YARDS, AT 2330 HOURS ON AUGUST 9, 1993, WHEN HE NOTICED VAPORS AND SOME LIQUID LEAKING FROM TOP OF TANK CAR ACFX 73184. DISPATCHERS OFFICE IN FAIRVIEW HEIGHTS, IL. WAS NOTIFIED AT 2335 AND MR. L.R. MILAM, CHEIF MECH. OFFICER, AT 2340.  THE WAYBILL IDENTIFIED THE COMMODITY AS SULFURIC ACID AND CALLS WERE PLACED TO CHEMTRAC AT 2355, ILLINOIS EMERGENCY RESPONSE AT 0135 (INCIDENT #932127) AND F.R.A. NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AT 0235 (INCIDENT #191561). A CONTAINMENT WAS BUILT BY MR. MILAN AND A MAINTENANCE OF WAY EMPLOYEE AROUND THE AREA OF THE SPILL.  MR. MILAM CALLED THE EMERGENCY DIVISION OF RHONE POULENC AT 01:35 AND WAS ADVISED THAT A REPRESENTATIVE FROM SHELL OIL COMPANY WOULD LOOK AT THE CAR.  THE REPRESENTATIVE FROM SHELL CALLED FOR DIRECTIONS AT APPROXIMATELY 02:15 AND ARRIVED AT 04:15.  IT WAS DETERMINED THE GASKET ON TOP OF THE CAR HAD RUPTURED ALLOWING THE LEAKAGE TO 20 TO 25 GALLONS OF ACID. THE GASKET WAS REPLACED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO MR. MILAN AT 04:30 AND THE CAR WA SCRUBBED AT 04:50 AND RELEASED AT 06:30 FOR FURTHER TANSPORTATION TO THE CUSTOMER.  CALLS WERE PLACED TO TWO (2) ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP COMPANIED BUT DUE TO THE FLOODING IN THE ST. LOUIS AREA, NEITHER COULD ADVISE WHEN THEY WOULD BE AVAILABLE.  A CALL WAS PLACED TO THE ILLINOIS ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY, REQUESTING THEIR AUTHORITY TO ALLOW THE USE OF LIME TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID AT THE SITE.  AFTER APPROVAL WAS GIVEN, FOUR (400) HUNDRED POUNDS OF AGRICULTURAL LIME WAS DUMPED AND COMPLETED AT 13:30.

PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE PRIMARY SORT.  ONE OF FOUR GALLON BOTTLES HAD A LOOSE CAP.  THE CONTENTS WERE REPACKED AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE DAMAGED CARTON WAS DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING UPS HAZMAT DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: TERRANCE CARTER, A C & C DRIVER WAS MAKING A DELIVER OF GASOLINE TO A TEXACO STATION FOR STAR ENTERPRISE AT 1600 LAPALCO BLVD IN HARVEY LA THE EVENING OF 080993.  AFTER MAKING CONNECTIONS TO THE TANK; THE DRIVER BEGAN HIS DELIVERY.  AFTER APPROXIMATELY 20 MINUTES GASOLINE BEGAN BLOWING BACK FROM THE FITTING.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE VAPOR RECOVERY WAS NOT WORKING PROPERLY CAUSING PRESSURE TO BUILD IN THE TANK.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE.  THE HAZMAT UNIT WAS ALSO NOTIFIED.  A CLEAN-UP CREW WAS USED TO CLEAN THE SPILL.  ABOUT 150 GALLONS.  WE HAVE INSTRUCTED OUR DRIVERS TO DOUBLE CHECK THE VAPOR RECOVERY FITTING TO MAKE SURE IT IS PROPERLY USED.  ALSO TO CHECK IF THE VAPOR RECOVERY IS CLEAR AND VENTING BACK TO THE TRAILER.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: TANK CAR RCRX 1272 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED.  CAR WAS ISOLATED.  SHIPPER - REAGENT CHEMICAL WAS CONTACTED THROUGH CHEMTREC. MR. DOUG WAGSTAFF 1-800-231-1807.  SHIPPER RESPONDED ON 8/5 - REPLACED BLOWN RUPTURE DISK.  CAR WAS RELOADED AT 14:00 8/6.
OP CENTER REPORTED LTC WHEN MOVED.  I CONTACTED SHIPPER WHO CONTRACTED GHTX MOSTE REPAIR TO REPLACE RUPTURE DISC.  CAR THEN SENT ON TO DESTINATION.

FLYT 2110 ARRIVED AT NDO AT 1850.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1855 THE DOCK CREW BEGAN TO NOTICE A STRONG SMELL COMING FROM BELLY 1 AND 2 AND ALSO THE TOP FLIGHT DECK. DAVID GREIDER IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE ILN HAZ MAT DESK TO VERIFY IF THERE WAS ANY HAZ MAT ON THE AIRCRAFT. THERE WAS NO HAZ PAPERWORK ON THE PLANE AND THE FLIGHT CREW KNEW OF NO HAZ MAT.  AT 1907 THE LEAKING CONTAINER HAD BEEN LOCATED.  DAVID GREIDER INSPECTED THE CONTAINER AND NOTED THAT THERE WAS A BOX THAT WAS WET ON THE BOTTOM AND SOME BOXES UNDER IT THAT WERE ALSO WET. THE CONTAINER WAS IMMEDIATELY CLOSED AND TAKEN TO AN AREA AWAY FROM THE AIRCRAFT AND BUILDING. ILN HAZMAT WAS CALLED AGAIN. AT THIS TIME TWO DOCK CREW PERSONNEL BEGAN TO EXPERIENCE HEADACHES, EYE IRRITATION AND DIZZINESS. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND PARAMEDICS ARRIVED AND BEGAN TO ADMINISTER FIRST AID TO THE TWO PERSONNEL. SHORTLY AFTER THIS ANOTHER DOCK EMPLOYEE CAME DOWN WITH THE SAME SYMPTOMS.  THE PARAMEDICS ALSO WANTED TO SEE THE ABX MECHANIC.  THE FOLLOWING WERE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT AND LATER RELEASED: DAVID HOLMES K & L COURIER CO. DEREK HOLMES K & L COURIER CO. TROY FARMER K & L COURIER CO. CHUCK BANKS ABX MECHANIC.  IN THE MEAN TIME THE FIRE DEPARTMENT EVACUATED THE WAREHOUSE BECAUSE THE WIND WAS BLOWING DIRECTLY INTO THE WAREHOUSE AND  OFFICE AREA.  AT THIS TIME THE FIRE DEPARTMENT COMPLETED CLEAN UP ON THE SPILL AT APPROXIMATELY 2140.  UNLOADING AND LOADING OPERATIONS WERE THEN RESTARTED AND COMPLETED. AT 2127 ANOTHER ABX FLORIDA SORT CENTER EMPLOYEE WAS FOUND PASSED OUT IN HIS TRUCK. APPARENTLY THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED FROM THE PLANE ON TO AN AWAITING TRUCK BEFORE IT WAS TO BE THE LEAKING CONTAINER, AND WAS MOVED TO A SAFE AREA.  THE PARAMEDICS RETURNED AND THE EMPLOYEE: GEOFF POTTER WAS TRANSPORTED TO FLORDIA HOSPITAL SOUTH FOR OVERNIGHT OBSERVATION.  SINCE THIS INCIDENT BOTH DEREK MACARTHUR AND GEOFF POTTER HAVE HAD TO RETURN TO THE HOSPITAL COMPLAINING OF CHEST PAINS AND BLOODY NOSES. THIS COMPLETES THE DESCRIPTION OF EVENTS FOR THE HAZ SPILL AT THE NDO STATION ORLANDO FL.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: THE N&M TRANSFER DRIVER NOTIFIED THE SAFETY MANAGER (C. KRICKEBERG) THAT A SMALL SPILL HAD OCCURED IN HIS TRAILER.  THE DRIVER BECAME AWARE OF THE SPILL WHEN STRONG FUMES BECAME APPARENT.  THE DRIVER CLIMBED OVER MOST OF THE CARGO IN THE TRAILER AND THEN IDENTIFIED A ONE GALLON JUG OF CLEANING COMPUND (CONTAINING HYDROCHLOURIC ACID) AS HAVING RUPTURED.  THE ONE GALLON CONTAINERS WERE BOXED FOUR TO A CARTON.  THERE WAS TWO CARTONS IN THE SHIPMENTS.  APPARENT CAUSE WAS A NAIL PORTRUDING FROM THE PALLET. DRIVER WAS SENT TO A HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION ONLY.  AFTER DISCOVERING THE RUPTURED JUG, THE DRIVER WAS SENT TO A LOCAL SHIPPING DOCK TO TRY TO HAVE HELP IN GETTING ACCESS TO THIS MATERIAL.  THE WISCONSIN RAPIDS POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE NOTIFIED, AS WELL AS THE WISCONSIN DNR.  THE REMAINING ACID WAS NEUTRALIZED BY A TEAM FROM GEORGIA PACIFIC.  FOAM INSERTS OR BUBBLE WRAP IN THE BOTTOM OF THE CORRUGATED CARTON MAY HAVE PREVENTED THIS JUG FROM BEING PUNCTURED.
column172: Container, no description given (do not use if at all possible)

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 11:10 AM, FRA INSPECTOR LEWIS RICHARDS, ACCOMPANIED BY PTRA CAR INSPECTOR WILLIAM SNEAD WERE INSPECTING CARS IN PTRA'S AMERICAN YARD.  THEY DISCOVERED TANX 23901 WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM AUXILIARY PIPE.  THE CAR WAS LEAKING VERY SLOWLY, LOOSING A DROP EVERY MINUTE OR SO.  UPON ARRIVAL BACK THE PTRA RIP TRACK OFFICE AT APPROX. 11:55 AM, MR SNEAD NOTIFIED WRITEUP MAN, LUPE CARMONA OF THE SITUATION.  MR. CARMONA IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE, KOPPERS COMPANY.  MR. WALTER GEELS FROM KOPPERS SAID HE WOULD HANDLE THE PROBLEM AND WOULD GET A CREW FROM UNION TANK CAR COMPANY TO TAKE A MOBILE REPAIR UNIT TO THE SITE AND REPAIR THE CAR.  WHEN I RETURNED TO RIP OFFICE FROM OTHER DUTIES AT APPROX. 12:45 PM, I WAS INFORMED OF THE INSTITUTION AND AFTER DISCUSSING IT WITH MR. RICHARDS, I WENT TO AMERICAN YARD, TRACK 202 TO SURVEY THE PROBLEM. I FOUND TANX 23901 TO BE LEAKING VERY SLOWLY FROM THE AUXILIARY PIPE DUE TO FAILURE OF THE CAULKING (USED AS GASKET MATERIAL). I CALLED FRA INSPECTOR RICHARDS FROM THE SITE AND ASKED IF CAR COULD BE MOVED TO KOPPERS TO UNLOAD.  HE STATED THE CAR COULD MOVE, KOPPERS HAD BEEN NOTIFIED AND HAS TAKEN STEPS TO HAVE CAR REPAIRED ON SITE.  I RETURNED TO RIP OFFICE AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30 PM.  WHEN MR CARMONA CALLED YARDMASTER GLEN COUCH AT APPROX.  5: PM, HE WAS INFORMED THAT THE UNION TANK CAR MOBILE UNIT WAS ON SITE AND CAR WAS BEING REPAIRED.  YARDMASTER COUCH INFORMED LUPE CARMONA THAT HE WAS UNABLE TO SET CAR IN KOPPERS TO UNLOAD UNTIL THE NEXT MORNING. CAR WAS REPAIRED AND SITUATION UNDER CONTROL AT APPROX 6:00 PM, 08-26-93.

PACKAGE DRIVER HAD PACKAGE BREAK OPEN FRIDAY NIGHT 8/13/93. HE HAD THE PACKAGE WRAPPED IN YELLOW BAG AND HELD FOR INSPECTION. HE ALSO CUT THE LABEL OFF OF THE BOX AND TOOK IT HOME TO BRING BACK WITH HIM ON MONDAY. HE FORGOT TO BRING IN THE LABEL. ON TUESDAY, HE BROUGHT THE LABEL IN AND I CALLED TO HAVE MSDS FAXED TO ME.  THE CONTENTS APPEARED TO BE HAZARDOUS. I TOOK THE DRIVER TO THE COMPANY DOCTOR TO BE CHECKED. ATTACHED IS A COPY OF THE MSDS, DOES NOT APPEAR TO BE A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. CONTENTS WERE PUT IN A PLASTIC BAG & ARE BEING HELD AT THE LODI CENTER, 1532 N BROADWAY, STOCKTON CA 95205, UNTIL DETERMINATION AS TO IF THE MATERIAL IS HAZARDOUS OR NOT.

column168: A FORKLIFT WAS BEING USED TO UNLOAD 300 GALLON TRANSPORTATION TOTE FORM A FLATBEG TRAILER OWNED BY PRIME, INC., SPRINGFIELD, MO.  THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR REPORTED THAT THE CONTAINER CAUGHT ON A TRAILER TIE-DOWN RING WHICH CAUSED THE CONTIANER TO SLIP OFF FROM THE FORK LIFT.  THE CONATIANER FELL ONTO THE GROUND ONTO ITS SIDE AND RELEASED 15 TO 20 GALLONS OF PAINT FROM A RUPTURED LID BEFORE THE CONTAINER COULD BE TURNED UPRIGHT. EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY TOOK ACTIONS TO CONTAIN AND RECOVER THE MATERIAL.  SOME MATERIAL ENTERED A STORM DRAIN WHICH INTERCEPTED LESS THAN SEVERAL TABLESPOONS OF PAINT.  IT APPEARED THAT NO PAINT ENTERED THE BROOK.  THE DROP INLET OF THE STORM DRAIN WAS CLEANED. THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO THE VERMONT AGENCY OF NATURAL RESOURCES AND TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (INCIDENT #193331).

column168: ON 8/18/93, AT APPROXIMATELY 0124 HOURS, I, KAREN NICHOLS/ HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR OF ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON OH 45177, INVESTIGATED A LEAKING SHIPMENT IN UNLOAD A OF OUR SORT FACILITY AT THE SAME ADDRESS.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PACKAGED IN A FIBREBOARD BOX WHICH HAD NO MARKINGS OR LABELS, NOR WERE THEY ANY ORIENTATION MARKINGS ON THE BOX. INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX WERE 3 GLASS BOTTLES WITH SCREWTYPE CLOSURES, EACH OF 500 ML CAPACITY.  THERE WERE NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURES WHICH ALLOWED 2 OF THE BOTTLES TO LEAK APPROXIMATELY 2 OZ EACH OF THE PRODUCT.  EACH GLASS BOTTLE HAD LABELS INDICATING THE CONTENTS TO BE ACETIC ACID, GLACIAL, CORROSIVE MATERIAL.  NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS USED. THE SHIPMENT IS CURRENTLY IN OUR HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY AND WILL BE FORWARDED WITH SHIPPER PREPARED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CERTIFICATION IN A D.O.T. APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM PENDING RELEASE BY THE FAA.

AS THE BOX CAME THROUGH THE SORT THE BOX WAS FOUND TO BE WET.  UPON OPENING THE BOX THE INNER PLASTIC BOTTLE'S CLOSURE HAD COME LOOSE AND ABOUT 1 OZ HAD LEAKED OUT.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTIANED WITHIN THE FIBREBOARD BOX.  THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED IN A STEEL SALVAGE DRUM AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  THE SHIPMENT IS BENIG HELD A DISPOSTION.

ON 08/3/93, AT APPROXIMATELY 0246 HRS, I, KAREN NICHOLS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR OF ABX AIR, INC. 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON OH 45177 INVESTIGATED A SHIPMENT BROUGHT TO MY ATTENTION BY JOHN SPRIGGS/SORT SUPERVISOR. THE SHIPMENT HAD NO HAZARD MARKINGS OR LABELS, NOR DID IT HAVE ANY SHIPPER'S CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THE SHIPMENT. THE FIRST CAN WHICH DID NOT LEAK AT ALL STATED "TBW25558 LOT #23348/FLAMMABLE LIQUID-SEVERE IRRITANT TO EYES AND SKIN." THE SECOND CAN STATED "TBW25556 LOT #23349". THE THIRD CAN STATED "TBW25557 LOT #23350.  THE 2ND AND 3RD CAN SHOW EVIDENTCE TO HAVE LEAKED ABSORBENT MATERIAL USED. PACKING PEANUTS WERE USED. THE SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD IN OUR HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.  UPON ITS RELEASE, THE SHIPMENT WILL BE MOVED WITH CERTIFICATION PROVIDED BY THE SHIPPER.

I RECEIVED NOTIFICATION FROM MR. JIM COX M.T.O. AT SALT LAKE REGARDING TANKCAR KCCX2426, HE REPORTS THAT THE CAR HAS BEEN SET OUT IN THE WASH TRACK AT THE ONE SPOT, FOR REPAIR. REGIONAL MANAGER R.M. STINE NOTED SLIGHT LEAKAGE FROM THE BASE OF THE SAFETY COVER PLATE. THE SAFETY VENT WAS MOUNTED ONTO HE MANWAY COVER PLATE. THE SAFETY VENT WAS EQUIPPED WITH A "GATX 261-53", DISC RETAINER/SPLASH DEFLECTOR. THE THREE STUDS WERE APPLIED TO THE COVER PLATE BY HAVING BEEN WELDED WHICH RESULTED IN THE STAINLESS STEEL DISC FLANGE NOT SETTING FLUSH ON THE COVER PLATE SURFACE.  ONE THIN RUBBER GASKET HAD BEEN APPLIED BETWEEN THE COVER PLATE AND THE DISC FLANGE HOWEVER A SLIGHT RELEASE HAD OCCURRED BETWEEN THIS JOINT. APPLIED "GORE-TEX" GASKET MATERIAL ON THE MANWAY SURFACE AND PROPERLY SECURED THE FITTING. THE BS & B 100 LB "FRANGIBLE DISC WAS INTACT.  VENT EQUIPPED WITH A SURGE BAFFLE.  MR. NORM SELF OF SIMPLOT WAS CONTRACTED AND HAS INDICATED THE CAR WILL BE REPAIRED AFTER BEING MADE EMPTY.

THE CAR DOES NOT APPEAR TO BE OVERLOADED ONGOING PROBLEM MAY BE DUE TO HANDLING, CONFERENCE WITH MR. WAGNER, HE WILL HAVE A WORD WITH THE CREW, SEE IF WE CAN GET THE CAR OUT OF TOWN WITHOUT FURTHER PROBLEMS.

ON 080693 AT 1430 HRS. I WAS NOTIFIED BY MR. MAURICE EVANS THE MANAGER OF MECHANICAL MTC.  AT STOCKTON, HE REPORTS TANKCAR KCCX2491 HAS BEEN SET OUT AT ELKO ON THE RIP TRACK 20, FOR REPAIR, IT IS REPORTEDLY LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  UPON ARRIVAL I INSPECTED THE TANKCAR AND FOUND THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISC WAS RUPTURED. THIS CAR HAD PRVIOUSLY BEEN REPAIRED AT SALT LAKE ON THE 073193 AND AGAIN ON 080393, IN EACH INSTANCE THE PROBLEM WAS THE SAME, RUPTURED DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY. ONCE AGAIN I REPAIRED THE CAR BY REPLACING THE DISC AND WASHING THE CAR WITH WATER AND SODA BICARBONATE, REPAIRS BEING COMPLETE AT 093093 HRS.  ON 080793.  I MADE CONTACT WITH THE CREW ON THE LOCAL, THAT HAD THE RESPONSIBILITY, OF MOVING THE CAR FROM ELKO TO WINNEMUCCA AND THEN BACK TO RED HOUSE, THE FIRST LEG OF THE MOVE TO WINNEMUCCA TO TAKE PLACE ON 080793 AND THE SECOND TO RED HOUSE ON 080993.  THE SAME CREW WOULD BE INVOLVED IN BOTH MOVES AND THEY STATED THAT THEY WOULD GIVE THE CAR EASY HANDELING. I CHECKED THE CAR FOR OVERLOAD AND FOUND THAT IT WAS INDEED OVERLOADED, I NOTIFIED MR. STAN ANDERSON THE MANAGER OF TRANSPORATION AT KENNECOTT COPPER REGARDING THE PROBLEMS WITH THE CAR, HE WAS APPRECIATIVE AND STATED THAT HE WOULD CHECK IT OUT AND LET ME KNOW WHAT HE FINDS.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER CTS, WAS NOTIFIED BY DON ERTLE, SUPV. YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CA., THAT TANK CAR UCLX 17009 WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR DURING NORMAL YARD SWITCHING OPERATIONS. ONE SWITCHPERSON WAS SPLASHED WITH THE COMMODITY AS THE CAR WAS BEING MOVED. THE CAR WAS LEFT IN YARD TRACK #13 AND ISOLATED PENDING AN INSPECTION. THE EMPLOYEE WAS TRANSPORTED TO BARSTOW COMMUNITY HOSPITAL. HE WAS EXAMINED AND RELEASED. MANAGER COOPER INSPECTED THE CAR AND DISCOVERED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE A BURST RUPTURE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT. THE SAFETY VENT WAS DISASSEMBLED, AND THE RUPTURE DISC REPLACED. THE COVER FOR THE SAFETY VENT WAS POLYPROPYLENE TRIVENT (FLAT AND TRIANGULAR IN SHAPE) WITH EXHAUST PORTS ON THE ENDS AND UNDERSIDE OF EACH OF THE THREE POINTS. THE END EXHAUST PORTS ON THE COVER WOULD ACCOUNT FOR THE PRODUCT SPRAYING AWAY FROM THE TANK CAR RATHER THAT BEING DEFLECTED DOWN ONTO THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR.  THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE ALSO INSPECTED AND FOUND TO BE PROPERLY SECURED.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.  DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPILLED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE NOT MADE TO THE

MR.GEORGE ELLSMORE THE CORRIDOR MANAGER FOR THE UTAH AREA CALLED ME AT 0847 HRS. AND REPORTED THAT THE MINPBV 10 AT GARFIELD UT. HAS A LEAKING TANKCAR, THE ARIX3007, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAR SHOULD BE BROUGHT INTO THE SALT LAKE YARD FOR REPAIR THIS WAS DONE AND THE CAR WAS SET OUT IN THE GOAT PIT AT 1040 HRS.  INSPECTION  REVEALED THAT THE 1/4" LIQUID LINE THAT FEEDS THE LIQUID GAUGE WAS EIGHTER  BROKEN OFF  OR HAD  COME LOOSE FROM ITS CONNECTION AT THE GAUGE, WHEN THE CABINET WAS OPENED LIQUID ARGON WAS SPRAYING THROUGHOUT THE INSIDE COVERING IT WITH ICE AND FROST. I THEN CALLED MR. KIRT KOMATSUBARA AT SACRAMENTO THE SHIPPER AND ASK WHAT HIS DESIRE WAS REGARDING THE CAR, HE STATED THAT HE WOULD HAVE TO CALL ME BACK. HE CALLED ME BACK AND PUT ME IN TOUCH WITH MR. JOHN SMITH AT AIRCO INDUSTRIAL GASES AT MURRAY HILL NEW JERSEY, WHO SUGGESTED THAT i SIMPLY CRIMP THE LINES WITH SOME VICE GRIP PLIERS. THIS WAS FINALLY ACCOMPLISHED WITH SOME DIFFICULTY, DUE TO THE FACT THAT YOU COULD NOT SEE BECAUSE OF THE ICE AND FOG AND THE CONTINUTING SPRAY OF LIQUID ARGON. WHEN THE LEAK WAS FINALLY STOPPED IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LINE HAD COME LOOSE FROM THE FITTING AT THE LIQUID GAUGE. WORK ON THE CAR WAS COMPLETE AT 1330 HRS. WITH NO FURTHER PROBLEMS, THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column172: Plastic container, no capacity or description given

column168: ON 8/31/93 AT ABOUT 0730 HOURS A.M. STEVE SPRINGER WAS UNLOADING A C CONTAINER WITH FREIGHT AT THE BUILDING WE USE TO SORT FREIGHT IN AT THE MARION WILLIAMSON COUNTY AIRPORT.  STEVE TOOK A BOX OUT OF A C CONTAINER THAT WAS GOING TO SEARS, 3000 W DEYOUNG, MARION IL.  62959.  HE PUT THIS BOX IN THE AREA WHERE MWA FRT IS LOADED, WHEN ASKED IF THE BOX WAS DROPPED STEVE DID ADVISE BE BENT OVER AND DID DROP IT FROM AT THE MOST ABOUT 1 FOOT ABOVE THE GROUND.  AFTER THE BOX WAS ON THE GROUND ANOTHER DRIVER SEAN BENJAMIN HEARD WHAT HE DESCRIBED AS A HISSING SOUND COMING FROM THE BOX AND HE ADVISED HIS SUPERVISOR ED GUTIERREZ.  ED TOOK THE BOX TO AN ISOLATED AREA AND PUT IT IN A PLASTIC BAG.  ABOUT THIS TIME I WAS GOING FROM OUR OFFICE IN THE TERMINAL BUILDING TO THE SORT BUILDING AND ED ADVISED ME ABOUT ANY NOISES AT THAT TIME BUT WAS WET ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX.  I LOOKED FOR ANY MARKINGS ON THE OUTSIDE THAT MIGHT ADVISE THE CONTENTS BUT THERE WAS NONE.  I OPENED THE BOX AND ON TOP THERE WERE SOME CIRCUIT BOARDS THAT HAD WHAT APPEARED TO BE ALUMINUM HOUSINGS AND WERE WRAPPED IN A BUBBLE PACK.  THERE WERE ALSO SOME DISPLAY MONITORS SIMILAR TO WHAT WOULD BE ON EXERCISE EQUIPMENT.  I REMOVED SOME OF THE CIRCUIT BOARDS AS IT WAS AT THE END OF THE BOX THAT WAS WET.  IN THE VERY BOTTOM OF THE BOX UNDER THESE CIRCUIT BOARDS WERE 4 AEROSOL CANS.  1 OF THE CANS HAD A HOLE NEAR THE BOTTOM OF THE CAN.  I REMOVED ONE OF THE CANS IN WHICH THE NAME ON THE CAN STATED "UNI SPORT SILICONE SPRAY" NEAR THE BOTTOM OF THE CAN THE FOLLOWING STATEMENT WAS PRINTED "DANGER: EXTREMELY FLAMMABLE CONTENTS UNDER PRESSURE"  I INSTRUCTED ED THAT THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT TO BE DELIVERED AND IT WAS TO REMAIN ISOLATED UNTIL I ADVISED WHAT TO DO WITH IT.  I THEN FOLLOWED THE PROCEDURES SET FOR HANDLING A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPILL AND CONTACTED OUT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SPECIALIST IN WILMINGTON, OHIO. I TALKED TO DON FLOREA IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DEPARTMENT WHO TOOK THE INFORMATION ABOUT THE SHIPMENT AND ADVISED HE WOULD CALL ME BACK.  IN ABOUT 10 MINUTES DON CALLED ME BACK AND ADVISED ME THAT WE NEEDED TO FILE A FORM 5800.1 AND ALSO THAT WE NEEDED TO ADVISE THE FAA WHICH I DID.

PICKED UP HAZARD, WITH GLOVES ON, FROM PD 2.  BROUGHT BACK TO PSC TABLE IN SPILL PAN.  OPENED PACKAGE UP AND POURED WHAT WAS LEFT INTO NEW CONTAINER, SEALED CONTAINER, WROTE MALLINCKRODT UP AND DAMAGE REPORT.  REPACKED CONTAINER AND SENT BACK.  CLEANED UP SPILL 8 OZ. WITH SOLUSORB.

THE FOLLOWING IS A LOG OF THE EVENTS TAKEN PLACE ON THE NEWARK BAY 262W REGARDING TANK CONTAINER HOYU 411011-5.  THIS LOG WAS RECORDED 0900 ON AUGUST 13, 1993 BY TODD REITER, DOUG RICHARDSON AND GUNTHER HOOCK. WEDNESDAY, AUGUST 11, 1993.  0500-VESSEL ARRIVED.  CHIEF MATE, JIM PAPPAS, NOTICED A GREEN LIQUID ON HATCH 13 STARBOARD SIDE WHICH WAS REACTING AND GIVING OFF A FOG LIKE VAPOR.  HE ALSO SAW THIS LIQUID FLOWING OVER THE SIDE OF THE VESSEL.  GERARD VAN DEN HEUVEL WAS CONTACTED BY CAPT. SCHRETZMAN AND NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL.  HE WAS ALSO TOLD THE VESSEL HAD ALREADY NOTIFIED THE US COAST GUARD.  GERARD CALLED AND UPDATED DOUG RICHARDSON.  0535-DOUG RICHARDSON ARRIVED AT THE MARINE TOWER. AT THE TIME, THERE WERE NO OTHER EMERGENCY RESPONSE PEOPLE IN.  0545-FIRST FIRE TRUCKS ARRIVE.  0620-DOUG CALLED AND UPDATED TODD REITER.  0630-FIRE DEPARTMENT SECURES FOLLOWING AREAS OF PORT: HIGH DOCK, 300 FIELD, ROW 100-108, ROW 200-208, MARINE TOWER-DEPARTMENT RELOCATED TO SHOP. 0700-TODD ARRIVES BUT COULD NOT GET CLOSE DUE TO AREAS CLOSED.  WENT TO MAIN OFFICE. 0730-DOUG CALLED AND UPDATED BOB MURPHY.  0800-LABOR-TWO GANGS START ON STANDBY.  MATE NOTIFIED DOUG IT LOOKED LIKE TANK WAS ON FORWARD END STARBOARD SIDE HATCH 13.  DOUG HAS LOCATED THREE POSSIBLE TANKS FROM THE PLAN WHICH COULD BE THE POSSIBLE LEAK ON HATCH 13.  HOYU 411011-IMCO 8.0, HOYU 411013-IMCO 8.0, HOYU 331088-IMCO 3.3.  ALL THREE TANKS ARE P&O HEATED TANKS.  GUNTHER AND TODD LOOK UP COMMODITIES IN SEA-LAND SYSTEM OF THE THREE TANKS AND WENT TO P&O OFFICE TO GET MORE DETAILED INFORMATION. 0800-NOTED EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS STILL ARRIVING ON SCENE.  0805-VAPORS STOPPED.   0810-DOUG GAVE THE SAME INFORMATION TO THE FIRE CHEIF. 0815-DOUG CALLED AND UPDATED BRIAN FITZGIBBON AND JIM DEVINE.  US COAST GUARD SENT PERSONNEL IN PROTECTIVE GEAR TO DO A VIDEO OF TANKS.  THE MEN RODE THE SPREADER BAR.  THEY VERIFIED LEAKAGE, OVERSPRAY AND LEAKAGE OVER THE SIDE.  COULD NOT CONFIRM WHICH CONTAINER IT WAS FROM. 0830-TODD CALLED MIKE AUGUSTINIAK. COULD NOT REACH HIM BUT LEFT MESSAGE ON PHONE MAIL. ALSO CALLED ALFRED TUNG, UPDATED HIM ON SITUATION AND DOUBLE CHECKED WITH HIM THAT WE HAD MADE NO PROCEDURE MISTAKES. 1030-ENTIRE YARD WAS OPENED EXCEPT FOR HIGH DOCK AND MARINE TOWER. 1130-LOOKS LIKE ALL EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS HAVE ARRIVED BY NOW. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: OUR VEHICLE DROPPED A WHEEL OFF THE EDGE OF THE ROAD, CAUSING THE DRIVER TO LOOSE CONTROL. THE TRUCK WENT DOWN A 50 FT. ENBANKMENT, CAUSING IT TO ROLL OVER. A SMALL HOLE WAS MADE IN THE TANK AND DUE TO THE LOCATION OF THE ACCIDENT, BY THE TIME WE GOT TO THE SITE AND TRANSFERRED THE REMAINING OIL TO ANOTHER UNIT, WE HAD LOSSED APPROX, 90 BARRELS OF CRUDE OIL. THE OIL APPERARED TO HAVE TRAVELED 100 YDS IN A SMALL DITCH. WE CONTACTED ENVROTECH INC. TO TAKE CARE OF THE ENTIRE CLEAN UP.  THEY WERE ON LOCATION THAT AFTERNOON AND DISCOVERED THAT THERE WERE SMALL CRACKS  IN THE DITCH, DUE TO THE DRY CONDITIONS, AND THE OIL HAD WENT UNDER GROUND FOR ANOTHER 100 YDS. ENVROTECH IS IN THE PROCESS OF DIGGING OUT ALL THE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND HAULING IT TO THEIR SOIL REMEDIATION SITE SOUTH OF BLOOMFIELD, NM. THE CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED IN APPROX, TWO WEEKS. THE SITE INSPECTED BY DENNY FOUST WITH THE O.C.D. ON AUGUST 25,1993.
CLOSURE WAS LOOSE AND CONTENTS LEAKED OUT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: SHIPMENT CAME IN ON TRAILER 15-8338 FROM PEI.  HOSTLER NOTICED FERRIC CHLORIDE LEAKING FROM THE BACK DOOR.  TRAILER WAS RUSHED TO THE DOCK WHERE ONE 30 GALLON DRUM WAS FOUND LAYING ON ITS SIDE WITH FERRIC CHLORIDE LEAKING FROM THE CAP.  DRUM WAS TURNED UPRIGHT AND SODA ASH WAS USED TO ABSORB THE SPILL.  THE CAP WAS TIGHTENED DOWN AND THE SHIPMENT WAS MOVED ON TO DESTINATION.  THE SODA ASH USED FOR CLEAN UP WAS PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM AND DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO FEDERAL REGULATIONS.

THE BATTERY ACID SPILL ON SOUTHWEST FLIGHT 762 FROM PHOENIX WAS CAUSED BY IMPROPER PACKING OF THE BATTERY BOX, (BATTERY ITSELF).  THE WHITE SEALING CAPS WERE NOT USED, THE PLASTIC SEALING BAG WAS NOT SEALED AND THE BOXES WERE NOT SECURED IN THE WEBBING TO PREVENT MOVEMENT.  THE PILL IN THE FORWARD BIN OF A/C 353, WAS TREATED WITH BAKING SODA AND CLEANED AND IT TOOK 10 MEN HOURS TO COMPLETE.
THE DRUMS CAME INTO US ON 4-WAY PALLETS.  BOB KESTNER LOADED 1 SKID IN THE TRAILER, AS HE LOADED ANOTHER PALLET THE SKID RUPTURED THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM WHEN HE WAS MOVING IT UP.

column168: WHILE INSPECTING TANK CAR GATX 40682, DETECTED A STRONG ODOR OF AMMONIA COMING FROM THE INSIDE OF THE PROTECTIVE HOUSTING.  UPON INSPECTION OF FITTINGS INSIDE THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING, I HEARD VAPOR BEING RELEASED AND WITH THE USE OF "SNOOP" LEAK DETECTOR, DETERMINED CAR TO BE LEAKING FROM THE PACKING NUTS ON THE "A" AND "B" LIQUID VALVES AND FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE O-RINGS.  RE-PACKED LIQUID VALVES WITH "GORTEX" PACKING MATERIAL & REPLACED THE O RINGS.  RE-PACKED LIQID VALVES WITH GORTEX PACKING MATERIAL & REPLACED THE O RINGS IN THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WITH BUNA N O RINGS.  ALL FITTINGS WERE THEN CHECKED WITH SNOOP LEAK DETECTOR. NOTIFICATIONS: 1630HRS, 8/27/93, CHEM-TREC, HOWARD MANNING, NEBRASKA DEPARTMENT ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, KIRK MORROW, #083093KM0900; 1550 HRS, 9/1/93 SF PHOSPHATES LIMITED, ED EYING, CAN SCHEER.  WHILE INSPECTING CAR NOTED THE SAFETY VALVE STENCILING RE-TEST DATE READ 1993.  BOTH LIQUID VALVES WERE RED TAGGED "LEAKS, BAD PACKING".  CONTACTED SHIPPER & SPOKE TO ED ERYING AND DAN SCHEER; CONTROL SPLST.  BOTH INDICATED THAT THEIR RECORDS INDICATED THE CAR WAS INTACT AND NOT LEAKING WHEN IT LEFT THEIR FACILITY AND THERE WAS NO DOCUMENTATION INDICATING THAT SOMEONE HAD TAGGED THE LIQUID VALVES AS BEING FAULTY.  AT 1130 HRS ON 9/1/93 CONTACTED FARMLAND INDUSTRIED & SPOKE TO JANE HEDENSKOG I ADVISED HER OF NOTED EXCEPTIONS, CORRECTIONS MADE & THAT THE SAFETY VALVE WAS DUE FOR RE-TEST.

column168: ON 082093 AT 0418 HRS THE CREST YARDMASTER IN N LITTLE ROCK, AR NOTIFIED CTS SPEC. M. KELLY THAT TANK CAR EDCX6203 IN TRCK 211 APPEARED TO BE LEAKING.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE CAR KELLY OBSERVED A SMALL CLOUD OF VAPOR ABOVE THE PROECTIVE HOUSING.  ON INSPECTION OF THE VALVES AND FITTINGS IN THE HOUSING, KELLY DETERMINED THAT THE SAFETY RELIEF DEVICE WAS ACTUATING ALLOWING PRODUCT TO BE RELEASED.  KELLY CONTACTED GERALD MARTIN WITH EL DORADO CHEMICAL AND INFORMED HIM OF THE PROBLEM WITH THE CAR.  MARTIN ADVISED THAT HE WOULD BE ENROUTE TO NLR TO INSPECT THE CAR.  MARTIN ARRIVED AT 1245 HRS AND AFTER INSPECTING THE CAR ADVISED THAT THE CAR HAD APPROX: 43 LBS OF PRESSURE BUILT UP IN IT CAUSING THE SAFETY RELIEF DEVICE TO ACTUATE.  MARTIN STATED THAT THE REASON FOR THE PRESSURE BUILD UP WAS THE HIGH AMBIENT TERMPERATURES AND THE LENGHTH OF TIME THE CAR HAD BEEN IN TRANSIT.  MARTIN AND KELLY PROCEEDEDTO SCRUB OFF THE PRESSURE DOWN TO 0 PSI AND THEY REPLACED THE SAFETY RELIEF DEVICE WITH A NEW ONE.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE IN TRANSIT TO IT'S POINT OF DESTINATION.

column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: (A & B) UNLOADING WAS BEGUN WITHOUT RAILCAR HAVING BEEN PROPELY BLOCKED AND  PROTECTED FROM MOVEMENT.  WHILE MANWAY COVER WAS OPEN AND UNLOADING OPERATIONS UNDERWAY THROUGH BOTTOM OUTLET, CAR ROLLED FREE FOR A DISTANCE OF APPROXIMATELY 100 FEET BEFORE STRIKING ANOTHER RAILCAR AND COMING TO REST.  DUE TO THE MOVEMENT OF THE CAR, THE UNLOADING LINE CONNECTED TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET WAS BROKEN, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO CONTINUE FLOWING.  THE IMPACT OF THIS CAR STRIKING THE OTHER TANK CAR, WHICH CONTAINED ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, RESULTED IN AN UNCONTROLLED RELEASE OF PRODUCT FROM THAT CAR ALSO, NECESSITATING AN EVACUATION OF THE ENTIRE AREA UNTIL SUCH TIME AS THE VALVES ON THE AMMONIA CAR COULD BE CLOSED, APPROXIMATELY FIVE HOURS LATER.  BECAUSE OF THE EVACUATION, IT WAS NOT FEASIBLE FOR PLANT PERSONNEL OR LOCAL AUTHORITIES TO APPROACH THE ACID CAR AND CLOSE THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE UNTIL AFTER ALL OF THE MATERIAL HAD DRAINED FROM THE CAR.  THE ENSUING VAPOR CLOUD ENGULFED THE ENTIRE FACILITY, ALONG WITHNEARBY U.S. HIGHWAY 30 AND THE UNION PACIFIC RIGHT OF WAY.  DUE TO THE SIZE OFTHE RELEASE AND THE SHIFTING OF WINDS, LOCAL AUTHORITIES EVENTUALLY EXTENDEDTHE EVACUATION TO A RADIUS OF TWO MILES.  LACK OF AVAILABLE PROTECTIVEEQUIPMENT PREVENTED SAFE ENTRY INTO THE SCENE BY LOCAL PERSONNEL IN ORDER TOCLOSE VALVES AND STOP LEAK.  APPROXIMATELY FIVE HOURS AFTER ONSET OF THEINCIDENT, UNION PACIFIC SPECIAL AGENT DECHANT WAS ABLE TO ENTER THE SCENE WITHLOCAL FIRE OFFICIALS AND CLOSE THE LIQUID AND VAPOR VALVES, WHICH STOPPED ALLLEAKS.  FOLLOWING A SHORT TIME INTERVAL FOR DISSIPATION OF VAPORS, STATEDEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY DETERMINED AREA SAFE FOR OPENING OFHIGHWAY, AND EVACUATION WAS LIFTED.

AT 1315 HRS ON 081393 I WAS NOTIFIED BY MR CECIL HARRIS THE CAR FOREMAN AT ELKO, HE REPORTS THAT ONCE AGAIN WAS HAVE THE KCCX 2491 IN THE ELKO YARD, IN LEAKING CONDITION.  AT 0730 HRS ON 081493 I INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISC WAS BROKEN OUT.  THSI WOULD BE THE 4 TH DISC REPALCEMENT IN THE SAME CAR STARING ON 073193 AGAIN ON 080393 AGAIN ON 080693 AND NOW ON 081493. THE CAR HAS BEEN WITHIN 78 MILES OF ITS DESTINATION SINCE THE 6TH OF AUGUST.  IN TALKKING WITH THE SHIPPER IT IS THEIR DESIRE TO DELIVER THE CAR IF POSSIBLE.  I MEASURED THE OUTAGE AND FOUND THAT IT WAS AT 61/4" THIS WAS REPORTED TO KENNECOT, MR. STAN ANDERSON, HE IS GOING TO CHECK THEIR RECORDS AND SEE IF THE CAR IS SET UP INCORRECTLY IN THE COMPUTER, TRY TO PREVENT THIS SITUATION IN THE FUTURE.  THE CONDUCTOR ON THE WORK TRAIN CALLED ME UPON DELIVERY OF THE CAR, HE REPORTS THAT IT WAS DELIVERED AT 1435 HRS. ON THE 081493 AND IT ARRIVED INTACT, NO LEAKS.  THERE WILL BE CONTINUED FOLLOW UP WITH KENNECOTT UTAH COPPER THIS CAR.

ON 8-25-93 LEAD SORTER, LYNN BAILEY, REPORTED A SHIPMENT THAT WAS LEAKING IN THE MAIN SORT.  I, MICHAEL FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST, MATT RAGER, RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE WE FOUND A FIBERBOARD.  WE OPENED THE FIBERBOARD BOX TO INVESTIGATE THE INNER CONTENTS.  INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX WE FOUND TWO MORE FIBERBOARD BOXES.  INSIDE THESE FIBERBOARD BOXES WERE AERSOL RECEPTICLES.  THERE WERE 12 ARESOL RECEPTICLES CONTAINING 13 OUNCES EACH. ONE OF THE AERSOL RECEPTICLES LEAKED.  ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE TWO INNER FIBERBOARD BOXES WERE THE FOLLOWING MARKINGS.  "THIS END UP, CONTENTS IN AERSOL CANS, INSIDE CONTAINERS COMPLY WITH PRESCRIBE REGULATIONS AND CONSUMER COMMODITY ORM-D".  NONE OF THESE MARKINGS WERE ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. THIS SHIPMENT IS AT THE HAZ MAT SORT, IN THE SECURITY CAGE, UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING RELEASE BY THE FAA.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS DELIVERING PRODUCT AT MOBIL OIL CORP.(M.O.C.) DARIEN, CT. NORTHBOUND SIDE, WHEN THE GASKET ON THE SITE GLASS FOR THE NO.2 COMPARTMENT FAILED. AS A RESULT OF THE RUPTURED GASKET, APPROXIMATELY (10-15) GALLONS SPILLED TO THE CEMENT PAD. SPILL PADS AND "SPEEDY DRY" CONTAINED AND ABSORBED THE PRODUCT, WHILE THE FIRE DEPT., THE D.E.P., AND MOBIL PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED. ASSISTANT CHIEF HUBBARD FROM THE FIRE DEPT. VISITED THE SCENE, ALONG WITH A MOBIL SUPERVISOR, AND DISPATCHER 211 FOR THE D.E.D. LOGGED THE CALL. THE TRAILER WAS IMMEDIATELY TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE, UNTIL THE GASKET AROUND THE SITE GLASS WAS REPLACED AND TESTED. NOTE: TRAILER ARE SCHEDULED ON A REGULAR BASIS FOR PREVENTATIVE MAINTENANCE CHECK UPS, AND THE TRAILER INVOLVED HAD ALL NEW GASKETS INSTALLED  EARLER IN THE WEEK.

column168: AUGUST 30, 1993-12:30: ANCON MARINE RECEIVED A CALL FROM PAT BRAUN, NYK LINE (NORTH AMERICA) INC. REQUESTING TO TALK WITH TROY HARDIN REGARDING A LEAKING CONTAINER.  15:00: CONTACT WITH LINDA FRAME WAS MADE.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE M/V CAPE CHARLES DISCOVERED A LEAKING TANK CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS PLACARDED "CORROSIVE AND FLAMMABLE" UN1298.  15:25: LINDA FAXED A COPY OF THE MSDS TO ANCON.  15:45: AFTER RECEIVING THE MSDS CARL W. GLASGOW, RESPONSE MANAGER FOR ANCON CALLED A MEETING WITH ANCON'S SAFETY MANAGER. OTHER SOURCES REFERENCED WERE: SAX, DOT AND ERM.  16:00: CARL GLASGOW DISCUSSED THE SAFETY ISSUES WITH PAT BRAUN OF NYK AND REQUESTED THE PHONE NUMBER OF THE MANUFACTURER.  DUE TO THE HAZARDS THIS CHEMICAL POSED ANCON RECOMMEDED THAT NYK FOLLOW THEIR CONTINGENCY PLAN FOR NOTIFICATION OF A POTENTIAL HAZARDOUS CHEMICAL RELEASE.  16:30: JERRY NEAT ANCON'S SAFETY OFFICER CONTACTED ED DORA, GE SILICONES, DIRECTOR OF EMERGENCY SERVICES. MR. DORAN VERIFIED THAT THIS CHEMICAL WAS WATER REACTIVE, HCI WOULD BE RELEASED AS A GAS SHOULD THERE BE CONTACT WITH AIR.  HE INDICATED THAT THE FACTORY PERSONNEL HANDLED THE MATERIAL ONLY IN LEVEL A PROTECTION.  17:00: RECEIVED A CALL FROM MR. DIETER HEGGER OF YUSEN TERMINALS INC (YTI) BERTH 212 LOS ANGELES HARBOR.  HE WAS CONCERNED ABOUT THE IMPACT THE LEAKING CONTAINER WOULD HAVE ON TERMINAL OPERATIONS AND WHAT COULD THEY DO TO FACILITATE THE SAFE OFFLOADING AND MITIGATION OF THE LEAKING CONTAINER. A MEETING FOR 0700 AT YTI WAS SET TO DISCUSS THE PROBLEMS OF UNLOADING THE CARGO.  18:30: IN A PHONE CONVERSATION WITH ED DORAN AND CARL GLASGOW REGARDING TRANSLOADING THE CONTAINER THE TRANSFER INSTRUCTIONS WERE DISCUSSED.  SEVERAL PAGES FROM THE EMERGENCY PROCEDURES MANUAL WAS FAXED TO ANCON.  19:30: CARL GLASGOW CONTACTED LT. SIMONS OF THE U.S COAST GUARD TO DISCUSS THE ARRIVAL OF THE M/V CAPE CHARLES.  HE INDICATED THAT LT. CUNNINGHAM WOULD CONTACT ANCON IN THE MORNING.  19:35: FAX WITH THE TRANSFER INFORMATION WAS RECEIVED AT ANCON.  CARL GLASGOW BEGAN A PROPOSED OPERATION PLAN FOR THIS TANK CONTAINER.  AUGUST 31-SEPTEMBER 10, 1993 NEGOTIATIONS AND CLEAN UP CONTINUED. (SEE ATTACHED).  SEPTEMBER 11, 1993 23:00: RUPTURE DISK FLANGE'S BOLT PATTERN DOES NOT MATCH THE PIPING FLANGE. SET SCREWS FIT BUT OUTER FLANGE BOLT PATTERN DIFFERENT.  (RUPTURE DISK FLANGE WAS BROUGHT TO THE SCENE BY GE SILICON PERSONNEL).  23:55: INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER BY GE SILICONE, COAST GUARD PERSONNEL.  DECON STARTED.  00:30: RELIEF VALVE, FLANGES AND PRESSURE GAUGE ALL ON TIGHTLY. RUPTURE DISK FLANGE ATTACHED WITH 5 BOLTS ONLY.  US COAST GUARD SATISFIED THAT THE CONTAINER IS SAFE FOR TRANSPORT ALONG THE HIGHWAY.  02:00: DEMOBILIZATION COMPLETE.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1700 HOURS ON AUGUST 30TH IN CONRAIL'S ALBANY FLEXI-FLO SITE, OPERATED UNDER CONTRACT BY BULK TRANSLOADING SERVICES, A BTS EMPLOYEE KEITH CAMPBELL, FAILED TO COMPLETELY OPEN A VAPOR RECOVERY VALVE. XYLENE WAS BEING TRANSFERRED FROM GATZ 27113 TO CHEMICAL LEAMAN TANK TRAILER 4369. THE TRAILER BECAME PRESSURIZED AND PRODUCT CAME OUT OF THE TRAILER STAND PIPE. BTS LOADER CAMPBELL WAS SPLASHED; CHEMICAL LEAMAN DRIVER GARY FINK INHALED VAPORS; AND MICHELLE M.HABURA, CAMPBELL'S GIRLFRIEND, HANDLED CONTAMINATED CLOTHING WHILE ASSISTING CAMPBELL. ALL THREE WERE TRANSPORTED TO ALBANY MEDICAL CENTER HOSPITAL; CAMPBELL AND HABURA WERE TREATED AND RELEASED FINK WAS ADMITTED.
DAMAGE WAS DISCOVERED BY OUTBOUND SUPERVISOR.  CLERK WAS NOTIFIED.  DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED IN SPILL TUB AND BROUGHT TO DAMAGE PROCESSING CENTER.  THE DAMAGE WAS DISPOSED OF USING THE PROPER DMP METHOD.

column168: MGR HARRY RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY THE NIGHT FORMAN AT THE CAR SHOP IN SALT LAKE THAT CAR UTLX48287 WAS THE SHOP FOR REPAIS AND THE REPAIRS HAD BEEN COMPLETED.  HOWEVER, AS THEY PUSHED THE CAR FROM THE SHOP HE COULD SMELL ETHER, NO LIQUID WAS OBSERVED.  INPECTION OF THE CAR, REVEALED THE MANWAY COVER TO BE LOOSE.  THE CAR WAS OPENED, THE GASKET CHECKED, AND FOUND TO BE INTACT AND IN GOOD SHAPE.  MANWAY WAS CLOSED AND TIGHTENED WITH A 36' WRENCH ALSO CHECKED THE UNLOADING ARRANGEMENT AND FOUND NO FURTHER PROBLEMS WITH THE CAR.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED AS WAS THE SHIPPER. REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED AT 0740 HRS. AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

ON 8-24-93 LEAD RAMP SORTER, GARY BARNES, REPORTED A WOODEN BOX THAT WAS LEAKING AND THAT IT WAS SETTING ON THE CEMENT.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS EMITTING AN ODOR.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE THE SHIPMENT WAS SETTING IN AN AREA AWAY FROM PERSONNEL.  UPON INVESTIGATION THE WOODEN BOX, I, MICHAEL FRYE. HAZARDOUS MTERIALS COORDINATOR, COULD NOT DETERMINE IF THE MATERIAL WAS REGULATED AS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST, MATT RAGER, DONNED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTIRIDGE RESPIRATOR TO PH THE LIQUID MATERIAL.  THE PH PAPER TURNED RED, WHICH INDICATED THE LIQUD WAS ACIDIC. THIS SHIPMENT WAS TAKEN TO THE HAZ MAT SORT AND HELD.  I, MICHAEL FRYE REQUESTED A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET ARRIVED THE NEXT DAY FROM THE SHIPPER.  IT LISTED THE CONTENTS AS: ALUMINUM CHLORIDE, SOLUTION, CORROSIVE, UN2581.  INSIDE THE WOODEN BOX WERE TWO, ONE GALLON GLASS RECEPTICLES.  THESE WERE PACKAGED WITH STYROFOAM PIECES FOR CUSHIONING.  BOTH GLASS RECEPTICLES WERE BROKEN. ALSO IN THE WOODEN BOX WAS A SMALL GLASS RECEPTICLES CONTAINING 200 GRAMS OF SODIUM SULFANILATE.  THIS MATERIAL DID NOT LEAK.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THIS SHIPMENT IS AT THE HAZ MAT SORT, IN THE SECURITY CAGE, PENDING RELEASE BY THE FAA.
